{"legislative_session": "2025A", "identifier": "HB25-1271", "title": "Federal Benefits for Youth in Foster Care", "from_organization": "~{\"classification\": \"lower\"}", "classification": ["bill"], "subject": [], "abstracts": [{"note": "summary", "abstract": "Beginning on or before July 1, 2026 July 1, 2027 , the bill requires a county department of human or social services (county department) to determine whether each a child or youth with a deceased parent in foster care and each youth participating in the foster youth in transition program (child or youth) may be eligible to receive survivor benefits administered by certain federal agencies, including the United States railroad retirement board, social security administration, or veterans administration (federal survivor benefits) within 90 days after placement the county department assumes custody . If the county department determines that the child or youth may be eligible, the county department shall apply for federal survivor benefits on behalf of the child or youth.\nUnder current law, certain federal agencies appoint a representative payee or fiduciary (representative payee) to receive and manage certain federal benefits on behalf of a child or youth in foster care, and a county department serving as a representative payee may use federal benefits to offset the cost of providing basic care and services to a child or youth in foster care its custody . The bill prohibits this benefit offset practice with respect to federal survivor benefits . Instead, the bill directs a county department serving as a representative payee to establish a trust an account for the federal survivor benefits (account). Money in the account is available for a limited set of current, unmet needs. Otherwise, the A county department serving as representative payee must save money in the account for the future needs of the individual child or youth.\nThe bill sets forth various accounting and notice requirements related to federal survivor benefits and requires the department of human services (department), in consultation with interested stakeholders, to establish guidance for county departments. The guidance extends to procedures for identifying a representative payee, disability screening for a child or youth, county department responsibilities when federal benefits are denied or when a child or youth leaves foster care, and policies governing access to account funds the establishment and maintenance of an account for federal survivor benefit funds . The department shall provide technical assistance to a county department during the 2025 and 2026 state fiscal years  about how to conserve those funds in the best interests of an individual child or youth .\n(Note: Italicized words indicate new material added to the original summary; dashes through words indicate deletions from the original summary.)\n(Note: This summary applies to the reengrossed version of this bill as introduced in the second house.)"}], "other_titles": [], "other_identifiers": [], "actions": [{"description": "Sent to the Governor", "date": "2025-05-14T06:00:00+00:00", "organization_id": "~{\"classification\": \"executive\"}", "classification": ["executive-receipt"], "related_entities": []}, {"description": "Signed by the President of the Senate", "date": "2025-05-14T06:00:00+00:00", "organization_id": "~{\"classification\": \"upper\"}", "classification": [], "related_entities": []}, {"description": "Signed by the Speaker of the House", "date": "2025-05-14T06:00:00+00:00", "organization_id": "~{\"classification\": \"lower\"}", "classification": [], "related_entities": []}, {"description": "House Considered Senate Amendments - Result was to Concur - Repass", "date": "2025-05-07T06:00:00+00:00", "organization_id": "~{\"classification\": \"lower\"}", "classification": [], "related_entities": []}, {"description": "House Considered Senate Amendments - Result was to Laid Over Daily", "date": "2025-05-06T06:00:00+00:00", "organizatio